questionRound.0.question.9.answer: I liked when i was second to last  or last because uncertainty in other players' choices was practically diminished. Their choices were easily predictable then and I could have full control over the choice that would benefit me most.

Basicly in all situations the last person to make a choice have only one choice to maximum his income  and we build on that. |  | plus due to the limit of numbers of players and flaw in game design  choose the row with second highest number always wins.

I usually chose the letters that had the highest pay-offs possible  for example  if the two possible pay offs were "42 and 12"  and "21 and 6"  I would choose "42 and 12".  Sometimes I based it off of what I expected the next color to choose  for example  if their highest pay off would come from YG  I would choose the letters that corresponded with YG to give me the highest pay-off possible.

questionRound.0.question.9.answer: I would try to think of what the next person might choose.

If I were the 2nd  3rd  or 4th role  then it took the least time to determine my move. The first move had already been made  which then 4th role would be able to play off of (as 1st role options were the other side of 4th role's square)  triggering a chain because 3rd role and 2nd role could anticipate the moves which would happen. As 1st role  I just followed this chain of actions both ways  following what would happen if I chose X or Y  and then seeing what result would be best for me (assuming the rest of the roles followed the logical path  which I'm pretty sure they always did  but there might have been some slip-ups). In general  though there were some exceptions  it seemed to work out that everyone got the second highest value within their square.

If I was the last pick  I would only need to look at the first pick to choose your optimal choice. If I was the first pick  second pick or third pick  I would have to assume what each pick would choose in order to maximize their own profit. I predict what the last pick would choose according to the first pick  then I would predict what the third pick would choose from what the last pick would choose and in the end i could predict what the second pick would choose from the third pick. Then I would be able to maximize my profit for every game if everybody was wanted to maximize their profit and be rational.

I tried to find which other player determined my score  while at the same trying to maximize the number of points that I would be able to obtain. Usually this was more difficult if I were the first two players to choose  and it was the easiest when I was the last person to choose.

If I was first  I worked backwards to see what people will choose if I chose X and what I would get from that. Then I compared with the winnings if I chose Y and went with the best result.  | If I wasn't first  I would see what others will choose based on what was already selected and used that to choose which answer I should put.

The last pick always had a no-brainer choice (one option yielded more tokens regardless of other players' choices). All players eventually started to base their choices around the chain optimizing tokens gained from the last pick's choice.

At first I extrapolated from the choices that had already been made to establish which decision would have the highest payoff assuming that every player would choose the option that gave them the highest payoff  but after a while I noticed that the best possible outcome was always the second highest payoff so I just started picking the options that led to those.

- everyone needs to pick the second highest digit available to them. If they don't the game will be too unpredictable. (don't be greedy! )  | - if going first  pick the second highest digit | - if last  see the choices already made and pick your highest v

I would go backwards and see what the last player would choose knowing what the first player played  and then what the second to the last player would play knowing what the last player played and then what the second played would play knowing what the second to the last played. It was the same process every round and the result I got from each of the rounds were mostly expected.
